---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import DocsSidebar from "../../components/DocsSidebar.astro";
---
<Layout title="Chrome extension · flipagent docs">
	<div class="cmw cmw-bordered">
		<div class="docs-shell">
			<DocsSidebar />
			<article class="docs-content">
				<h1>Chrome extension</h1>
				<p class="lead">The flipagent extension drives <code>/v1/orders/*</code> inside your real Chrome — your TLS fingerprint, your cookies, your eBay account. Akamai sees a normal session.</p>

				<h2>Why this exists</h2>
				<p>eBay's buy-flow uses Akamai bot detection. A headless or scripted browser gets challenged or shadow-banned within minutes. Running the buy clicks inside your existing Chrome — pinned to the eBay tab you actually log into — reuses the trust profile your account already has. The hosted API queues a <code>purchase_order_id</code>; the extension polls for it via <code>/v1/bridge/poll</code>, navigates the listing, places the order, and posts the result back via <code>/v1/bridge/result</code>.</p>
				<p>Future iteration will swap to eBay's official Order API once tenant approval lands. Same SDK + MCP surface — <code>client.orders.*</code> won't change.</p>

				<h2>Install (developer / unpacked)</h2>
				<p>The extension isn't on the Chrome Web Store yet. To install from source:</p>
				<ol>
					<li>Clone the repo and build: <code>npm install &amp;&amp; npm run --workspace @flipagent/extension build</code></li>
					<li>Open <code>chrome://extensions</code> and enable <strong>Developer mode</strong> (top-right toggle)</li>
					<li>Click <strong>Load unpacked</strong> and select <code>packages/extension/dist/</code></li>
					<li>Pin the extension to your toolbar so the popup is one click away</li>
				</ol>

				<h2>Pair it with your API key</h2>
				<ol>
					<li>Open the options page: right-click the extension icon → <strong>Options</strong> (or visit <code>chrome-extension://&lt;id&gt;/options.html</code>)</li>
					<li>Paste your <code>fa_…</code> API key. Get one from your <a href="/dashboard/">dashboard</a>, or for self-host run <code>npm run --workspace @flipagent/api issue-key -- you@example.com</code></li>
					<li>Click <strong>Save + pair</strong>. The extension calls <code>POST /v1/bridge/tokens</code> with your API key to mint a long-lived bridge token (<code>fbt_…</code>); the API key never leaves the options page after that.</li>
					<li>Self-host? Set the API base URL to <code>http://localhost:4000</code> (or your host) before pairing.</li>
				</ol>
				<p>Once paired, the popup shows a green dot when the service worker is polling. The dashboard's eBay panel reflects the same state.</p>

				<h2>Sign into eBay (one-time)</h2>
				<p>The extension drives buy-flow inside whatever eBay session your Chrome already has. If you're not signed in, click <strong>Sign in to eBay</strong> in the popup — the extension opens <code>ebay.com/signin</code> in a new tab, you sign in normally, and from then on the cookies stay with your profile. The extension reports session state via <code>POST /v1/bridge/login-status</code> so the api knows whether it's worth dispatching jobs.</p>

				<h2>Place an order from your agent</h2>
				<p>Once paired + signed in, anything that hits the bridge surface works:</p>
				<div class="code">
					<div class="code-head"><div class="dot-row"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div><span>node</span></div>
<pre><code>{`import { createFlipagentClient } from "@flipagent/sdk";

const client = createFlipagentClient({ apiKey: "fa_…" });

const { purchaseOrderId } = await client.orders.checkout({
  itemId: "v1|123456789|0",
  maxPriceCents: 12_000,
});

// Poll until terminal — extension drives the buy flow in the meantime.
const order = await client.orders.wait(purchaseOrderId);
console.log(order.status); // "completed" | "failed" | "cancelled" | "expired"`}</code></pre>
				</div>
				<p>From Claude Desktop / Cursor via MCP, the same flow runs through the <code>ebay_buy_item</code> + <code>ebay_order_status</code> tools.</p>

				<h2>Status states</h2>
				<table class="api">
					<thead>
						<tr><th>Status</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
					</thead>
					<tbody>
						<tr><td><code>queued</code></td><td>API accepted, waiting for the extension to claim it.</td></tr>
						<tr><td><code>claimed</code></td><td>Extension picked it up via <code>/v1/bridge/poll</code> and is loading the listing.</td></tr>
						<tr><td><code>awaiting_user_confirm</code></td><td>Listing loaded, BIN clicked, waiting for the user to OK the in-browser confirmation prompt.</td></tr>
						<tr><td><code>placing</code></td><td>User confirmed; the extension is clicking <em>Confirm and pay</em>.</td></tr>
						<tr><td><code>completed</code></td><td>eBay order id captured. The hosted API posts a <code>order.completed</code> webhook.</td></tr>
						<tr><td><code>failed</code></td><td>Selector miss, listing ended, price changed past <code>maxPriceCents</code>, or eBay error. Reason in <code>failureReason</code>.</td></tr>
						<tr><td><code>cancelled</code></td><td>Cancelled via <code>POST /v1/orders/:id/cancel</code> while non-terminal.</td></tr>
						<tr><td><code>expired</code></td><td>No extension claimed the job within <code>expires_at</code>. Usually means the extension isn't running or isn't paired.</td></tr>
					</tbody>
				</table>

				<h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>Orders sit at <code>queued</code> forever.</strong> The extension isn't running. Open <code>chrome://extensions</code>, click <strong>service worker</strong> under the flipagent row to inspect logs, and confirm the alarms tick fires every ~30s. MV3 service workers sleep aggressively; a click on the extension popup wakes it instantly.</li>
					<li><strong><code>buy_it_now_not_found</code> / <code>confirm_and_pay_not_found</code> failures.</strong> eBay rotated the DOM. Patch the selector candidates in <code>packages/extension/src/content.ts</code> and rebuild. Future plan: server-side recipes so hotfixes don't need a Web Store re-review.</li>
					<li><strong>Pair fails with 401.</strong> Your API key is wrong or revoked. Re-issue from the dashboard, or run <code>flipagent doctor</code> to confirm scope.</li>
					<li><strong>Self-host: extension can't reach localhost.</strong> The manifest already host-permits <code>http://localhost:4000</code> and <code>http://localhost:4001</code>. Use one of those; for other ports rebuild after editing <code>manifest.json</code>.</li>
				</ul>

				<h2>What the extension can read + send</h2>
				<p>Permissions in the manifest: <code>storage</code> (your bridge token + settings), <code>alarms</code> (30-second poll), <code>tabs</code> (open the listing tab), <code>scripting</code> (inject the buy-flow script), <code>cookies</code> (probe whether you're signed into eBay). Host permissions are scoped to <code>ebay.com</code> and the flipagent api — nothing else.</p>
				<p>The extension never reads other browser tabs, never persists cookies anywhere, and never sees plaintext your API key after the first pair-and-store cycle (only the <code>fbt_…</code> bridge token).</p>
			</article>
		</div>
	</div>
</Layout>
